# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coq-prover
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] In mathematical logic and computer science, the **calculus of constructions** (**CoC**) is a type theory created by Thierry Coquand.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] It can serve as both a typed programming language and as constructive foundation for mathematics.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] For this second reason, the CoC and its variants have been the basis for Rocq and other proof assistants.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] Some of its variants include the calculus of inductive constructions (which adds inductive types), the calculus of (co)inductive constructions (which adds coinduction), and the predicative calculus of inductive constructions (which removes some impredicativity).
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The CoC is a higher-order typed lambda calculus, initially developed by Thierry Coquand.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] It is well known for being at the top of Barendregt's lambda cube.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] It is possible within CoC to define functions from terms to terms, terms to types, types to types, and from types to terms.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The CoC is strongly normalizing, and hence consistent.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The CoC has been developed alongside the Rocq proof assistant.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] As features were added (or possible liabilities removed) to the theory, they became available in Rocq.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] Variants of the CoC are used in other proof assistants, such as Matita and Lean.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The calculus of constructions can be considered an extension of the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The Curry–Howard isomorphism associates a term in the simply typed lambda calculus with each natural-deduction proof in intuitionistic propositional logic.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The calculus of constructions extends this isomorphism to proofs in the full intuitionistic predicate calculus, which includes proofs of quantified statements (which we will also call "propositions").
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] 5. $\mathbf {T}$ itself, which is the type of large types.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] As with the untyped lambda calculus, the calculus of constructions uses a basic notion of equivalence of terms, known as $\beta$ -equivalence.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The valid judgments for the calculus of constructions are derivable from a set of inference rules.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] In the following, we use $\Gamma$ to mean a sequence of type assignments $x_{1}:A_{1},x_{2}:A_{2},\ldots$ ; $A,B,C,D$ to mean terms; and $K,L$ to mean either $\mathbf {P}$ or $\mathbf {T}$ .
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] We shall write $B[x:=N]$ to mean the result of substituting the term N for the free variable x in the term B .
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] The calculus of constructions has very few basic operators: the only logical operator for forming propositions is $\forall$ .
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] Booleans and Naturals are defined in the same way as in Church encoding.
[src:coq-prover/calculus-of-constructions] However, added problems arise from propositional extensionality and proof irrelevance.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The **Rocq Prover** (formerly named **Coq**) is an interactive theorem prover first released in 1989.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] It allows the expression of mathematical assertions, mechanical checking of proofs of these assertions, assists in finding formal proofs using proof automation routines and extraction of a certified program from the constructive proof of its formal specification.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Rocq works within the theory of the calculus of inductive constructions, a derivative of the calculus of constructions.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Rocq is not an automated theorem prover but includes automatic theorem proving tactics (procedures) and various decision procedures.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The Association for Computing Machinery awarded Thierry Coquand, Gérard Huet, Christine Paulin-Mohring, Bruno Barras, Jean-Christophe Filliâtre, Hugo Herbelin, Chetan Murthy, Yves Bertot, and Pierre Castéran with the 2013 ACM Software System Award for Rocq (when it was named Coq).
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] When viewed as a programming language, Rocq implements a dependently typed functional programming model; when viewed as a logical system, it implements a higher-order type theory.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The development of Rocq has been supported since 1984 by French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (INRIA), in collaboration with many other French and international research institutions.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The development of Rocq was initiated by Gérard Huet and Thierry Coquand, and more than 200 people, mainly researchers, have contributed features to the core system since its inception.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The implementation team has successively been coordinated by Gérard Huet, Christine Paulin-Mohring, Hugo Herbelin, and Matthieu Sozeau.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Rocq is mainly implemented in OCaml with a bit of C.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The core system can be extended by way of a plug-in mechanism.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Rocq provides a specification language named Gallina.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Programs written in Gallina have the weak normalization property, implying that they always terminate.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] This is a distinctive property of the language, since infinite loops (non-terminating programs) are common in other programming languages.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] As an example of a proof written in Rocq, consider a proof of a lemma which states that taking the successor of a natural number flips its parity.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The fold-unfold tactic introduced by Danvy is used to help keep the proof simple.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] This proof firsts import the definition of booleans and natural numbers from the standard library, and then defines a `is_even` which is a function returning whether a number is even.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Then, three lemmas are proven about this function.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The first just restate the defining equations of `is_even`, and since Rocq knows the equations their proof is very short.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The last lemma is proven with a case distinction after first applying the second lemma; the star `*` demarks that a new sub-case starts there.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Georges Gonthier of Microsoft Research in Cambridge, England and Benjamin Werner of INRIA used Rocq to create a surveyable proof of the four color theorem, which was completed in 2002.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Their work led to the development of the SSReflect ("Small Scale Reflection") package, which was a significant extension to Rocq.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Despite its name, most of the features added to Rocq by SSReflect are general-purpose features and are not limited to the computational reflective programming style of proof.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] SSReflect is distributed as part of the main Rocq distribution since Coq 8.7.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] In addition to constructing Gallina terms explicitly, Rocq supports the use of *tactics* written in the built-in language Ltac or in OCaml.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] These tactics automate the construction of proofs, carrying out trivial or obvious steps in proofs.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Several tactics implement decision procedures for various theories.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] For example, the "ring" tactic decides the theory of equality modulo ring or semiring axioms via associative-commutative rewriting.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Built-in decision procedures are also available for the empty theory ("congruence"), propositional logic ("tauto"), quantifier-free linear integer arithmetic ("lia"), and linear rational/real arithmetic ("lra").
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Further decision procedures have been developed as libraries, including one for Kleene algebras and another for certain geometric goals.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The old name **Coq** means 'rooster' in French and is a wordplay on the name of Thierry Coquand, *calculus of constructions* or *CoC*, and stems from a French tradition of naming research development tools after animals.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] Until 1991, Coquand was implementing a language named the *calculus of constructions* and it was simply called *CoC* then.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] On October 11, 2023, the development team announced that *Coq* would be renamed *The Rocq Prover* in coming months, and began updating the code base, website, and related tools.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The official renaming happened with the release of Rocq 9.0 in March 2025.
[src:coq-prover/coq-software] The new name refers to Inria Rocquencourt, where the system was developed first, and is related to the mythical bird Roc, which allows keeping the bird references from the prior name.
[src:coq-prover/doc] You can explore the Rocq & Rocq Platform packages documentation, guides, exercises, and books to enhance your knowledge.
[src:coq-prover/doc] For newcomers interested in programming languages, the Software Foundations series is an excellent introduction to using the Rocq Prover for formal verification.
[src:coq-prover/doc] For newcomers with a background in mathematics rather than computer science, this book is an introduction to the Rocq Prover and to the SSReflect proof language used in the Mathematical Components library.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Accustomed Rocq users will find a substantial account of the formalization style that made the Mathematical Components library possible.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The primary audience of the manuscript are the readers with expertise in software development and programming and knowledge of discrete mathematic disciplines on the level of an undergraduate university program.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The low-level goal of this course is to provide an overview of the Rocq Prover, taken in its both incarnations: as an expressive functional programming language with dependent types and as a proof assistant providing support for mechanized interactive theorem proving.
[src:coq-prover/doc] This textbook is a foundational book that introduces readers to the Rocq Prover and its underlying formal system, the Calculus of Inductive Constructions (CIC).
[src:coq-prover/doc] The book provides a comprehensive guide to interactive theorem proving, combining theory with practical applications.
[src:coq-prover/doc] It covers key concepts such as inductive types, recursive functions, and proof construction, while offering numerous examples and case studies, including the formalization of algorithms and mathematical proofs.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Coq'Art serves as both an introduction for beginners and a reference for experts, making it an essential resource for anyone working with Rocq or exploring formal methods.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Verified Functional Algorithms shows how a variety of fundamental data structures can be specified and mechanically verified.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Formal Reasoning About Programs (FRAP) is a book that provides a general introduction to formal logical reasoning about the correctness of programs and to using Rocq for this purpose.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The main narrative of FRAP presents standard program-proof ideas, without rigorous proofs.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Matching Rocq code then show how to make it rigorous.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Interleaved with that narrative, there are also other lectures' worth of material, for building up more practical background on Rocq itself.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Certified Programming with Dependent Types (CPDT) is a hands-on guide to advanced programming and proving using the Rocq Prover.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The book focuses on leveraging Roqc’s dependent type system to write certified programs, where correctness is formally verified alongside implementation.
[src:coq-prover/doc] It introduces key concepts such as inductive types, type theory, proof automation, and advanced tactics, providing a blend of theoretical foundations and practical examples.
[src:coq-prover/doc] CPDT is particularly known for its focus on proof engineering and building large-scale verified systems efficiently.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Aimed at readers with some prior exposure to Rocq, it serves as an invaluable resource for those looking to master the interplay between programming and formal verification.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Floating-point arithmetic is ubiquitous in modern computing, as it is the tool of choice to approximate real numbers.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Due to its limited range and precision, its use can become quite involved and potentially lead to numerous failures.
[src:coq-prover/doc] One way to greatly increase confidence in floating-point software is by computer-assisted verification of its correctness proofs.
[src:coq-prover/doc] This book provides a comprehensive view of how to formally specify and verify tricky floating-point algorithms with the Coq proof assistant.
[src:coq-prover/doc] It describes the Flocq formalization of floating-point arithmetic and some methods to automate theorem proofs.
[src:coq-prover/doc] It then presents the specification and verification of various algorithms, from error-free transformations to a numerical scheme for a partial differential equation.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The examples cover not only mathematical algorithms but also C programs as well as issues related to compilation.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Aspiring towards greater understanding of Rocq and its underlying theory?
[src:coq-prover/doc] Coq is built around a well-delimited kernel that performs type checking for definitions in a variant of the Calculus of Inductive Constructions (CIC).
[src:coq-prover/doc] Although the metatheory of CIC is very stable and reliable, the correctness of its implementation in Coq is less clear.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Indeed, implementing an efficient type checker for CIC is a rather complex task, and many parts of the code rely on implicit invariants which can easily be broken by further evolution of the code.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Therefore, on average, one critical bug has been found every year in Coq.
[src:coq-prover/doc] This paper presents the first implementation of a type checker for the kernel of Coq (without the module system, template polymorphism and η-conversion), which is proven sound and complete in Coq with respect to its formal specification.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Our work is based on the MetaCoq project which provides meta-programming facilities to work with terms and declarations at the level of the kernel.
[src:coq-prover/doc] We verify a relatively efficient type checker based on the specification of the typing relation of the Polymorphic, Cumulative Calculus of Inductive Constructions (PCUIC) at the basis of Coq.
[src:coq-prover/doc] It is worth mentioning that during the verification process, we have found a source of incompleteness in Coq’s official type checker, which has then been fixed in Coq 8.14 thanks to our work.
[src:coq-prover/doc] In addition to the kernel implementation, another essential feature of Coq is the so-called extraction mechanism: the production of executable code in functional languages from Coq definitions.
[src:coq-prover/doc] We present a verified version of this subtle type and proof erasure step, therefore enabling the verified extraction of a safe type checker for Coq in the future.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Coq version 8.20 adds a new rewrite rule mechanism along with a few new features, a host of improvements to the virtual machine, the notation system, Ltac2 and the standard library.
[src:coq-prover/doc] In interactive theorem proving, a range of different representations may be available for a single mathematical concept, and some proofs may rely on several representations.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Without automated support such as proof transfer, theorems available with different representations cannot be combined, without light to major manual input from the user.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Tools with such a purpose exist, but in proof assistants based on dependent type theory, it still requires human effort to prove transfer, whereas it is obvious and often left implicit on paper.
[src:coq-prover/doc] This paper presents Trocq, a new proof transfer framework, based on a generalization of the univalent parametricity translation, thanks to a new formulation of type equivalence.
[src:coq-prover/doc] This translation takes care to avoid dependency on the axiom of univalence for transfers in a delimited class of statements, and may be used with relations that are not necessarily isomorphisms.
[src:coq-prover/doc] We motivate and apply our framework on a set of examples designed to show that it unifies several existing proof transfer tools.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The article also discusses an implementation of this translation for the Coq proof assistant, in the Coq-Elpi metalanguage.
[src:coq-prover/doc] One of the central claims of fame of the Coq proof assistant is extraction, i.e., the ability to obtain efficient programs in industrial programming languages such as OCaml, Haskell, or Scheme from programs written in Coq's expressive dependent type theory.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Extraction is of great practical usefulness, used crucially e.g., in the CompCert project.
[src:coq-prover/doc] However, for such executables obtained by extraction, the extraction process is part of the trusted code base (TCB), as are Coq's kernel and the compiler used to compile the extracted code.
[src:coq-prover/doc] The extraction process contains intricate semantic transformation of programs that rely on subtle operational features of both the source and target language.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Its code has also evolved since the last theoretical exposition in the seminal PhD thesis of Pierre Letouzey.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Furthermore, while the exact correctness statements for the execution of extracted code are described clearly in academic literature, the interoperability with unverified code has never been investigated formally, and yet is used in virtually every project relying on extraction.
[src:coq-prover/doc] In this paper, we describe the development of a novel extraction pipeline from Coq to OCaml, implemented and verified in Coq itself, with a clear correctness theorem and guarantees for safe interoperability.
[src:coq-prover/doc] We build our work on the MetaCoq project, which aims at decreasing the TCB of Coq's kernel by reimplementing it in Coq itself and proving it correct w.r.t. a formal specification of Coq's type theory in Coq.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Since OCaml does not have a formal specification, we make use of the Malfunction project specifying the semantics of the intermediate language of the OCaml compiler.
[src:coq-prover/doc] Our work fills some gaps in the literature and highlights important differences between the operational semantics of Coq programs and their extracted variants.
[src:coq-prover/doc] In particular, we focus on the guarantees that can be provided for interoperability with unverified code, identify guarantees that are infeasible to provide, and raise interesting open question regarding semantic guarantees that could be provided.
[src:coq-prover/doc] As central result, we prove that extracted programs of first-order data type are correct and can safely interoperate, whereas for higher-order programs already simple interoperations can lead to incorrect behaviour and even outright segfaults.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] In computer science and mathematical logic, a **proof assistant** or **interactive theorem prover** is a software tool to assist with the development of formal proofs by human–machine collaboration.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] This involves some sort of interactive proof editor, or other interface, with which a human can guide the search for proofs, the details of which are stored in, and some steps provided by, a computer.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] A recent effort within this field is making these tools use artificial intelligence to automate the formalization of ordinary mathematics.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Because of this small size, some automated proof checking systems can have less than a thousand lines of core code, and are thus themselves amenable to both hand-checking and automated software verification.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] The Mizar system, HOL Light, and Metamath are examples of automated proof checking systems.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Automated proof checking can be done either as a batch operation, or interactively, as part of an interactive theorem proving system.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Automath, which was developed by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn starting in 1967, is often considered the first proof checker and the first system to utilize the Curry–Howard correspondence between programs and proofs.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Automath was used by L.S. van Benthem Jutting in 1977 to formalize Landau's *Foundations of Analysis*, which was the first formalization of the real numbers.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] In 1973, Robert Boyer and J Moore published *Proving Theorems about LISP Functions* which aimed to verify programs, not mathematics.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Their theorem prover is now known as ACL2.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] In the 1970s, Edinburgh LCF introduced the idea of using a functional programming language as the metalanguage for a theorem prover, and led to the HOL family of proof assistants.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] The 1990s saw the rise of Rocq, (then known as Coq), which has been used for many large-scale formalization projects.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Since the late 2010s, Lean, a proof assistant strongly influenced by Rocq, has become another popular choice, especially for formalizing mathematics.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] A commonly used front-end for proof assistants was the Emacs-based Proof General, developed at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Nowadays, many provers include their own editor.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Rocq includes RocqIDE, which is based on OCaml/Gtk.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Isabelle includes Isabelle/jEdit, which is based on jEdit and the Isabelle/Scala infrastructure for document-oriented proof processing.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] More recently, Visual Studio Code extensions have been developed for Rocq, Isabelle by Makarius Wenzel, and for Lean 4 by the leanprover developers.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Freek Wiedijk has been keeping a ranking of proof assistants by the amount of formalized theorems out of a list of 100 well-known theorems.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] As of September 2025, only six systems have formalized proofs of more than 70% of the theorems, namely Isabelle, HOL Light, Lean, Rocq, Metamath and Mizar.
[src:coq-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] The following is a list of notable proofs that have been formalized within proof assistants.
[src:coq-prover/refman] This is the reference manual of the Rocq Prover.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Rocq is a proof assistant or interactive theorem prover.
[src:coq-prover/refman] It lets you formalize mathematical concepts and then helps you interactively generate machine-checked proofs of theorems.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Machine checking gives users much more confidence that the proofs are correct compared to human-generated and -checked proofs.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Rocq has been used in a number of flagship verification projects, including the CompCert verified C compiler, and has served to verify the proof of the four color theorem (among many other mathematical formalizations).
[src:coq-prover/refman] Users generate proofs by entering a series of tactics that constitute steps in the proof.
[src:coq-prover/refman] There are many built-in tactics, some of which are elementary, while others implement complex decision procedures (such as `lia`, a decision procedure for linear integer arithmetic).
[src:coq-prover/refman] Ltac and its planned replacement, Ltac2, provide languages to define new tactics by combining existing tactics with looping and conditional constructs.
[src:coq-prover/refman] These permit automation of large parts of proofs and sometimes entire proofs.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Furthermore, users can add novel tactics or functionality by creating Rocq plugins using OCaml.
[src:coq-prover/refman] The Rocq kernel, a small part of the Rocq Prover, does the final verification that the tactic-generated proof is valid.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Usually the tactic-generated proof is indeed correct, but delegating proof verification to the kernel means that even if a tactic is buggy, it won't be able to introduce an incorrect proof into the system.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Finally, Rocq also supports extraction of verified programs to programming languages such as OCaml and Haskell.
[src:coq-prover/refman] This provides a way of executing Rocq code efficiently and can be used to create verified software libraries.
[src:coq-prover/refman] To learn Rocq, beginners are advised to first start with a tutorial / book.
[src:coq-prover/refman] Several such tutorials / books are listed at https://rocq-prover.org/docs.
